    <segment id="1" parent="11" relname="circumstance">Given this is the beginning of the 4th week of the course,</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="27" relname="span"> a lot of our discussions so far have focused on HCI concepts such as user-centeredness, transparency, etc.</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="24" relname="span"> In this discussion, other concepts are creeping in that are no less important -- things like flexibility, ease of use, ease of learning, consistency, error recovery, and such.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="25" relname="span"> Actually, these terms begin to describe the attributes of usability.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="2" relname="evaluation"> It is important that we know how to define usability.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="32" relname="span"> As you begin to prepare your first assignment paper, Software Evaluation, </segment>
    <segment id="13" parent="26" relname="span">this is a good time to discuss usability and usability attributes in depth.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="35" relname="span"> Let&apos;s discuss these concepts in view of what makes good user-centered design: </segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="23" relname="list">

ease of use </segment>
    <segment id="14" parent="23" relname="list">
ease of learning or learnabililty </segment>
    <segment id="15" parent="23" relname="list">
efficiency </segment>
    <segment id="16" parent="23" relname="list">
memorability </segment>
    <segment id="17" parent="23" relname="list">
error recovery </segment>
    <segment id="18" parent="23" relname="list">
user satisfaction </segment>
    <segment id="19" parent="23" relname="list">
flexibility </segment>
    <segment id="20" parent="23" relname="list">
consistency </segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="35" relname="elaboration">

And we can also draw out usability issues by focusing on the usability principles discussed in our texts.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="30" relname="span"> Again, these attributes and principles are important for us to understand the depth the usability beyond our common sense intuition of what we think usability is.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="21" relname="condition"> If we have a handle on these,</segment>
    <segment id="21" parent="29" relname="span"> then we begin to see how we can &quot;measure&quot; usability.</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="22" relname="circumstance"> 
As we did with HCI Concepts and Terms,</segment>
    <segment id="22" parent="28" relname="span"> let&apos;s explore these attributes one by one.</segment>
